<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-699-834  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 699 834.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Computing  August 1989 p30(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Take a closer look.andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer-based vision systems are nearly 100 percent accurate, andmake objective inspections and tight quality control possible.andO;Machine vision systems are best suited to the industrial tasks ofgauging, identification of objects by simple pattern recognition,optical character recognition, monitoring of high volumeprocesses, quality inspection, and robot guidance.andP;  There arecurrently over 700 such systems in the UK, and their benefitsinclude providing useful production data, reducing wastage,improving process control, and saving time.andP;  Plug-in board-basedvision systems for microcomputers are available from suchsuppliers as Image Inspection and Cortex.andP;  More expensiveVMEbus-based systems, priced from about 7,500 pounds sterling, areideally suited for rigors of the factory floor.andP;  These areavailable from such suppliers as Computer Recognition Systems,Allen-Bradley, and Image Automation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     VisionSystemsApplicationsQuality ControlManufacturersUnited Kingdom.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>